<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="529" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,651,1947]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,759,784]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Large body size (body length: 19.1 mm; wing length: 15.9 mm), light brown, with faint yellow markings in the live specimen (Fig. 
<number box="[557,572,795,819]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="9.0">9</number>
) [which became darker and disappeared in the dried, pinned specimen] (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1640,1663]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,189,1598]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,189,1598]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Exetasis jujuyensis Gillung sp. nov. A. lateral view; B. dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217501/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">
Fig. 
<number box="[151,166,831,855]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
), without black spots, covered by dense, yellow pilosity; antennae as long as the head (see Remarks), with a narrow, elongate flagellum; wing relatively long, extending beyond the tip of abdomen, without markings; abdomen globose.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="529" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,651,1947]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,939,964]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">Description.</emphasis>
Female: 
<emphasis box="[451,511,940,964]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">Head</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[528,609,939,963]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1640,1663]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,189,1598]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,189,1598]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Exetasis jujuyensis Gillung sp. nov. A. lateral view; B. dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217501/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">
Figs. 
<number box="[593,609,939,963]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="3.9">3</number>
</figureCitation>
, 9). Antenna as long as the head; scape twice as long as pedicel; pedicel short, cylindrical; flagellum black, cylindrical and narrowed at the apex, bearing numerous terminal setae (see Comments); frons black, small and flattened; ocellar tubercle reduced, quadrangular in shape; two ocelli present; mouthparts very reduced, composed of a tiny proboscis bearing numerous terminal setae. 
<emphasis box="[1206,1287,1048,1072]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">Thorax</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1306,1389,1048,1072]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1640,1663]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,189,1598]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,189,1598]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Exetasis jujuyensis Gillung sp. nov. A. lateral view; B. dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217501/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">
Figs. 
<number box="[1373,1389,1048,1072]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="3.9">3</number>
</figureCitation>
, 9). Brown, slightly lighter than abdomen, with faint light yellow markings; coxae, femora and tarsus light brown; tibiae dark brown; calypter dark brown, with margins even darker. 
<emphasis box="[915,971,1121,1144]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">Wing</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[990,1060,1120,1144]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1970,1993]" captionTargetBox="[239,1361,404,1864]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[210,1378,306,1954]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Exetasis wings. A. E. brasiliensis Carrera; B. E. jujuyensis Gillung sp. nov.; C. E. calida Wiedemann (modified from Wiedemann 1830, plate VII, fig. 2 b). Scale line = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217500/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">
Fig. 
<number box="[1044,1060,1120,1144]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
B). Wing membrane light brown, without markings; microtrichia present only on costal cell; subcosta ending beyond the middle of the wing; R 
<number box="[1412,1420,1171,1185]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="2.0">2</number>
+ 
<number box="[1429,1436,1171,1185]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="3.0">3</number>
slightly curved at the apex; R 
<number box="[486,494,1209,1223]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="4.0">4</number>
+ 
<number box="[503,510,1209,1223]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="5.0">5</number>
reaching wing margin; M 
<number box="[807,815,1209,1223]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="1.0">1</number>
and M 
<number box="[896,904,1209,1223]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="2.0">2</number>
ending before wing margin; M 
<number box="[1260,1268,1209,1223]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="3.0">3</number>
fused to CuA 
<number box="[1428,1436,1209,1223]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="1.0">1</number>
both basally and distally of cell m 
<number box="[535,543,1248,1262]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="3.0">3</number>
; CuA 
<number box="[612,620,1248,1262]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="2.0">2</number>
fused with A 
<number box="[773,781,1248,1262]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="1.0">1</number>
before wing margin; A 
<number box="[1047,1055,1248,1262]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="2.0">2</number>
very short. 
<emphasis box="[1191,1297,1233,1257]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">Abdomen</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1313,1393,1233,1257]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1640,1663]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,189,1598]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,189,1598]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Exetasis jujuyensis Gillung sp. nov. A. lateral view; B. dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217501/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">
Figs. 
<number box="[1377,1393,1233,1257]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="3.9">3</number>
</figureCitation>
, 9). Globose; tergites light brown; sternites dark brown. 
<taxonomicName box="[733,855,1272,1296]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Combretaceae" genus="Terminalia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[733,855,1272,1296]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">Terminalia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Tergites VII and VIII with the same form as tergite VI, but smaller; tergite IX semicircular, with posterior margin black, thickened, bearing numerous black hairs; sternites VI and VII square; sternite VIII square, with posterior margin trilobate, presenting numerous black spines; hypoproct barely visible, almost fused with cerci; cerci yellow, with numerous yellow hairs.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="529" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,651,1947]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1416,1440]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">Remarks</emphasis>
. Both the antennae are broken off in the pinned specimen so they are not shown in 
<figureCitation box="[1238,1305,1416,1440]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1640,1663]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,189,1598]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,189,1598]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Exetasis jujuyensis Gillung sp. nov. A. lateral view; B. dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217501/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">
Fig. 
<number box="[1289,1305,1416,1440]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
. They were then placed in a microvial on the pin with the specimen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="529" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,651,1947]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,1488,1512]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">Etymology</emphasis>
. The species is named 
<taxonomicName box="[588,801,1489,1512]" class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Exetasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jujuyensis">
<emphasis box="[588,801,1489,1512]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">Exetasis jujuyensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in reference to the province Jujuy, where the spider was collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="535" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,651,1947]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1559,1584]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">Comments</emphasis>
. This Argentinean species is the only non-Brazilian representative of the genus and can be readily differentiated from all other 
<taxonomicName box="[474,567,1597,1620]" class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Exetasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[474,567,1597,1620]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">Exetasis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species based on the large body size, light brown body coloration with faint yellow markings and narrow, elongate flagellum. 
<taxonomicName authority="Gillung" authorityName="Gillung" box="[736,1050,1632,1656]" class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Exetasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jujuyensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[736,953,1633,1656]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">Exetasis jujuyensis</emphasis>
Gillung
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1062,1157,1632,1656]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1062,1157,1632,1656]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Exetasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="calida">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">E. calida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, sharing the fusion of veins M 
<number box="[564,572,1683,1697]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="3.0">3</number>
and CuA 
<number box="[679,687,1683,1697]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="1.0">1</number>
both basally and distally of cell m 
<number box="[1073,1081,1683,1697]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="3.0">3</number>
. Only the female is known.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,651,1947]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,377,1706,1731]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">Biological data</emphasis>
. After being kept in the laboratory for approximately eight months, the spider began to weave a &quot;silk bed&quot; in a depression made in the substrate for molting. Although it adopted the belly up normal position of molting (Baerg 
<number box="[327,384,1779,1803]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="1958.0">1958</number>
) it did not complete the molting process. The spider died 
<number box="[1029,1056,1779,1803]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="11.0">11</number>
hours later and an acrocerid larva of five millimeters in diameter emerged through a hole made ??in the ventral part of the abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[1309,1391,1815,1839]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1482,1505]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,195,1457]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,195,1458]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Acanthoscurria sternalis, size of parasitoid’s emergence opening." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217502/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">
Figs. 
<number box="[1375,1391,1815,1839]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="4.5">4</number>
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1405,1421,1815,1839]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1948,1971]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,937,1900]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,937,1901]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Acanthoscurria sternalis, dead spider showing the parasitoid’s emergence opening." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217503/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">5</figureCitation>
). Before emergence, the parasite ate most of the soft parts of the spider, causing its death. The larva then began to move and left a slime trail while heading up to reach the tree trunk that served as the spider’s refuge (
<figureCitation box="[1290,1359,1887,1911]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1871,1894]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,517,1806]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,517,1808]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. Exetasis jujuyensis Gillung sp. nov. larva attached to the spider tree trunk shelter." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217504/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="529">
Fig. 
<number box="[1343,1359,1887,1911]" pageId="4" pageNumber="529" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
). Only a single larva emerged from the spider host.
</paragraph>
<caption box="[151,966,1640,1663]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217501/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="530" targetBox="[151,1435,189,1598]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,966,1640,1663]" box="[151,966,1640,1663]" pageId="5" pageNumber="530">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1640,1663]" pageId="5" pageNumber="530">FIGURE 3.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Gillung" authorityName="Gillung" box="[281,556,1641,1663]" class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Exetasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="530" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jujuyensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[281,473,1642,1663]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="530">Exetasis jujuyensis</emphasis>
Gillung
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[563,675,1641,1662]" pageId="5" pageNumber="530">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[563,643,1641,1662]" pageId="5" pageNumber="530" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
A.
</emphasis>
lateral view; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,836,1641,1662]" pageId="5" pageNumber="530">B.</emphasis>
dorsal view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1711,1879]" pageId="5" pageNumber="530">
The recently emerged larva (
<figureCitation box="[529,600,1711,1735]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1871,1894]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,517,1806]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,517,1808]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. Exetasis jujuyensis Gillung sp. nov. larva attached to the spider tree trunk shelter." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217504/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="530">
Fig. 
<number box="[584,600,1711,1735]" pageId="5" pageNumber="530" value="6.7">6</number>
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[614,629,1711,1735]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,981,1004]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,223,956]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,223,956]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Exetasis jujuyensis Gillung sp. nov. larva. A. lateral view; B. dorsolateral view, showing the pair of spiracles; C. dorsal view, showing the cephalic zone." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217505/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="530">7</figureCitation>
) presented a pair of dark brown (almost black) spiracles (
<figureCitation box="[1297,1367,1711,1735]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,981,1004]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,223,956]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,223,956]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Exetasis jujuyensis Gillung sp. nov. larva. A. lateral view; B. dorsolateral view, showing the pair of spiracles; C. dorsal view, showing the cephalic zone." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217505/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="530">
Fig. 
<number box="[1352,1367,1712,1735]" pageId="5" pageNumber="530" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
B, C). Eleven days after emergence, the larva developed a cephalic zone, a globose portion that would later turn into the adult head (
<figureCitation box="[287,357,1783,1807]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,981,1004]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,223,956]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,223,956]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Exetasis jujuyensis Gillung sp. nov. larva. A. lateral view; B. dorsolateral view, showing the pair of spiracles; C. dorsal view, showing the cephalic zone." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217505/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="530">
Fig. 
<number box="[342,357,1783,1807]" pageId="5" pageNumber="530" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
C). Seventeen days post-emergence, the larva reached the pupal stage, with clearly developed head and eyes, thorax with retracted legs and wings of half the adult size also retracted on the venter of the thorax (
<figureCitation box="[159,227,1855,1879]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1861,1884]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1106,1840]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,1106,1841]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 8. Exetasis jujuyensis Gillung sp. nov. pupa. A. dorsal view; B. lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217506/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="530">
Fig. 
<number box="[211,227,1855,1879]" pageId="5" pageNumber="530" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
). Finally, after 
<number box="[399,427,1855,1879]" pageId="5" pageNumber="530" value="34.0">34</number>
days the female adult emerged (Fig. 
<number box="[843,859,1855,1879]" pageId="5" pageNumber="530" value="9.0">9</number>
).
</paragraph>
